Here’s a potential extension: **Constraint-Aware Latent Probes (CALP)**. These would be lightweight, frozen probes trained *once* on diverse constraint-annotated corpora (e.g., grammaticality, logical consistency, entity grounding) to detect when generations deviate from desired properties. Unlike fine-tuned classifiers, these wouldn’t require per-task adaptation. Their outputs could serve as soft constraint signals, dynamically fused with hard constraints (e.g., regex-based token masking or grammar-guided beams) during decoding.

The key innovation would be a **constraint composition layer**—a small, trainable module that learns to weight and reconcile conflicting signals (e.g., “must include drug name” vs. “avoid overly technical terms”) using only meta-information about constraint types (hard/soft, strictness level, domain). This avoids full retraining while enabling zero-shot transfer to new constraint combinations.

This approach complements NSCV by reducing reliance on real-time symbolic execution, potentially improving speed and coverage. It also opens up self-supervised avenues: can we mine implicit constraints from model explanations (e.g., attention patterns, residual stream trajectories) to bootstrap probe training?

Thoughts? Could this direction enhance robustness in high-stakes settings—say, generating patient discharge summaries under multiple regulatory and linguistic constraints—where both safety and fluency are critical?
